                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d126">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">810.20 Defense/148<hi rend="superscript"
                    >3/12</hi>: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Ecuador</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Long</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Quito</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-06-20T10:00:00-05:00"
                            >June 20, 1940—10 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received 5:45 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>122. Referring to the Department’s telegram No. 57, June 3, 3 p.m.<note n="46"
                        xml:id="d126fn1">See footnote 31, <ref target="#pg_17">p. 17</ref>.</note> a
                    conference was held between the Ministers of Foreign Affairs and National
                    Defense, Canaga, Harris and myself with regard to the defense of the Americas,
                    last night. The Foreign Minister reasserted Ecuador’s intention to stand by
                    conference agreements and both Tobar and Plaza asserted the disposition of their
                    Government to cooperate in every practical way. They are also prepared to hold
                    staff conferences any time after July 10.</p>
                <p rend="center">. . . . . . . . . . . . . .</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Long</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
